@superbobry IMHO if I were you, I would only switch from `LGPL` to `GPL` (most likely v3). It is the best license if you are concerned about the act of sharing of your code and the ownership on it, as it is a strong *copyleft license that requires anyone who distributes your code or a derivative work to make the source available under the same terms, and also provides an express grant of patent rights from contributors to users.*<sup>1</sup>

It is not true, that *most* projects are under these simpler licenses, as a matter of fact, all the great and successful FOSS ones are under `GPL` (mostly v2 for historical reasons).

<sup>1</sup> [Choose an open source license](https://choosealicense.com)

After a bit of poking around, I found the following: https://patchwork.kernel.org/patch/5144161/

Changing BrotliRBit() to the following fixed the asm call to rbit on arm64:

```
#if BROTLI_MODERN_COMPILER || defined(__llvm__)
#if defined(BROTLI_TARGET_ARMV7) || defined(BROTLI_TARGET_ARMV8)
static BROTLI_INLINE unsigned BrotliRBit(unsigned input) {
  unsigned output;
#if defined(BROTLI_TARGET_ARMV8)
  __asm__("rbit %w0, %w1" : "=r" (output) : "r" (input));
#elif defined(BROTLI_TARGET_ARMV7)
  __asm__("rbit %0, %1\n" : "=r"(output) : "r"(input));
#endif
  return output;
}
#define BROTLI_RBIT(x) BrotliRBit(x)
#endif  /* armv7 || arm64 */
#endif  /* gcc || clang */

```

With this change, both arm 32 and 64 bit targets compile and execute correctly.

