@groutr, I don't think my group ever got those extra features to be recognized for setuptools in our packages, but they must be working for someone!  In any case, they *are* working for pip -- e.g. "pip install ipython[notebook]" (which installs extra packages not installed with just "pip install ipython".   I think that's effectively what Michael is proposing for conda, and I agreed that it would be very useful.

However, pip (and setuptools?) optional packages are about providing extra packages that are *not* installed by default, and thus they address category "optional" in my proposal above.  At least for the projects I am involved in, it's much more urgent to move some of what conda currently considers "dependencies" into a different category "suggested".  The key here is that the default behavior of conda would not change for our currently supported packages -- by default, exactly the same packages would get installed whether the dependencies were listed as suggested or required.  But if given a special flag, conda would then install only the hard dependencies, not the suggested ones.  

I think this approach is distinct from and complementary to support for extra "optional" explicitly specified packages.  E.g. current conda users might be alarmed if they suddenly find all their useful tools disappearing in a new release, because we no longer consider them hard dependencies, so that they now have to explicitly install each one.  Instead, we can keep installing everything we think is useful or supported, just as we do now, but simply provide some mechanism for people to tell conda to install only the *core* or *required* dependencies.

@johanneskoester I've looked briefly at a couple of the examples you link to in the GGD project, and it's not immediately clear to me why there has been a choice of pre-link over post-link.  Or, alternately, why post-link is not equivalent to pre-link in this case.  Note that post-link is not being deprecated, only pre-link.

The reason behind deprecating pre-link is that it is primarily used to make changes to the package cache rather than the install prefix, often in non-idempotent ways, and can therefore have an effect on *all* conda environments a package is installed into, not just the target environment of the current conda invocation.

What's being done here may well end up being a legitimate use case for pre-link, and I'm definitely open to finding an alternate solution than blanket deprecation if that turns out to be true.

